      "summary": "Independent *prakaraṇa* in eight chapters whose stated purpose is to establish (*siddhi*) the *iṣṭa* — the desired tenet, namely *brahmātmaikya*. The method is dialectical. Vimuktātman takes up each opposed analysis of erroneous cognition — *ātma-khyāti* of the Vijñānavādins, *asat-khyāti* of the Mādhyamikas as here construed, *anyathā-khyāti* of the Naiyāyikas, *akhyāti* of the Prābhākaras — and shows each to fail on its own terms; *anirvacanīya-khyāti* survives as the only coherent account. He defends *bhāva-rūpā-anirvacanīya-avidyā* with Brahman as locus, examines the *avaccheda-vāda* and *pratibimba-vāda* analyses of the *jīva* and inclines toward the latter, and refutes Bhedābheda and the proto-realist alternatives of his day. Jñānottama's *Vivaraṇa* is the principal sub-commentary. Vidyāraṇya cites the treatise as authoritative in the *Vivaraṇa-Prameya-Saṃgraha*; Madhusūdana cites it in the *Advaita-Siddhi*. Much of the technical machinery later Advaitins use to discuss *adhyāsa* and avidyā originates here.",
