          "first_use_gloss": "(roughly: ignorance as appearance-making power)"
        },
        {
          "term_iast": "avidyā",
          "first_use_gloss": "(roughly: beginningless ignorance)"
        },
        {
          "term_iast": "anirvacanīya",
          "first_use_gloss": "(roughly: not determinately sayable as either of two opposed predicates)"
        },
        {
          "term_iast": "sat / asat",
          "first_use_gloss": "(roughly: being / non-being as mutually opposed ontic predicates)"
        }
      ],
      "why_this_passage": "This is one of the clearest local formulations of the doctrine for which Vimuktātman is classically cited: avidyā is not collapsed into non-being, nor simply reified as ordinary being, but argued to be sadasadvilakṣaṇa. The passage states the thesis in his own technical vocabulary rather than leaving it to later summaries.",
